title: Grateful Dead Live at Cameron Indoor Stadium, Duke U on 1976-09-23
description:
Set 1

Mississippi Half Step, Minglewood Blues, Ramble On Rose, Cassidy, Brown Eyed Women, Lazy Lightning-> Supplication, Crazy Fingers-> El Paso, It Must Have Been The Roses, The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Help On The Way-> Slipknot!-> Franklin's Tower-> Looks Like Rain, Eyes Of The World-> Samson & Delilah, High Time, Dancin' In The Streets-> Wharf Rat-> Drums-> The Other One-> Morning Dew

reviews.review_text: Sound. Considering the claims about the sources for this being half way through the first set I'd say it it is a pretty sweet little offering for those of us who are fans of the in between kind of 76 dead scene,definitly worth a listen or two.
do not overlook Very inspired second set. The Eyes prefigures Englishtown a year later.

crap recording- but half of it is good Cassidy through Warfrat is great sbd quality except for a 1 minute aud patch at the end of Eyes. But the other one is ruined as is teh Dew with a crap audience patch. Why anyone likes audience quality is beyond me. Like I want to hear some 'yahooer' during Dew...I recorded this show with my streaming audio recorder becuase the help slip is hot. I have just about all of these boards digital already. I am happy to share since I bought all of the dead official releases and they still don't know what their fans want I can share the good soundboards- not Dave's picks- but your picks.  I am happy to share- bjm_chinacat@hotmail.com I have just about every show in circulation.

....the last show I need to complete my 1976 CD collection...!! Who's got it on CD and wants to trade a copy?  I've got 5,000 hours of GD on CD to trade.

Email me at "clegg AT supernet DOT COM".  Include the phrase "Grateful Dead 9-23-76" in the subject line.  I will reply to ALL emails....


THANKS GANG

Thoughts with ONE day left before a week of sitting on a lake watching the world go by I think this Archive of Dead concerts, sessions, etc, all of which have different sound and performance quality, is kind of like golf. Every time I play a round I may get a crappy score, but there are golden moments here and there. 
I just found a used record store near where I work, it's run by a couple of old hippies, one of whom is a Deadhead, the other doesn't like the band very much. I told them about the Archive, also bought the only 2 Grateful Dead CD's they had.

- This show kicks ass! 1976 seems to be a very mixed year, but this is one of the gems. It sounds like Garcia is using the neck pickup on his Travis Bean a lot, and it's a very sweet tone. Fantastic jams!

Get Some! Not the best sound, but not the worst, and Phil has some sort of Quadraphonic effect going on that is just fantastic. Vocals suffer the most. Aside from nitpicking the sound, the band is off the wall this night. njpg guy even endorses this show, and he is very selective. Hope we find the MRs someday for a Dave's Pick release. 

Oh yeah, and this is the best "High Time" I have ever heard. Jerry's vocals are so pure.
